{"title_page": "Hal Summers", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{unreferenced|date=June 2015}}\n'''Henry Forbes Summers''' (18 August 1911 in [[Harrogate]], [[Yorkshire]] \u2013 22 December 2005 in [[Basingstoke]], [[Hampshire]]), aka '''Hal Summers''', was a senior British civil servant. He published several volumes of [[poetry]].\n\nSummers was educated at [[Fettes College]], [[Edinburgh]] and [[Trinity College, Oxford]]. He joined the Ministry of Health in 1935.  He was Private Secretary to [[Aneurin Bevan]] while he was Minister of Health, during the passage of the National Health Bill, 1945.\n\nHe moved to the [[Ministry of Housing and Local Government]] on its creation and was promoted to Under-Secretary in 1955.  This ministry was later absorbed into the [[Secretary of State for the Environment|Department of the Environment]].  He was made a [[Order of the Bath|CB]] in 1961 and retired in 1971.\n\n== Publications ==\n*''Smoke After Flame'', 1944\n*''Hinterland'', 1947\n*''Poems in Pamphlet IV: Visions of Time'', 1952\n*''Tomorrow is my Love'', 1978\n*''The Burning Book'', 1982\n*''Brevities'', 1991\n\nHis most popular poems include \"My Old Cat\" (voted one of Britain's favourite 20th-century poems in a [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] poll), \"The Beginners\" and \"The Seed\".\n\n==References==\n* [[Who's Who (UK)|Who was Who]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Summers, Hal}}\n[[Category:Private secretaries in the British Civil Service]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Ministry of Health (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Ministry of Housing and Local Government]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Department of the Environment]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Fettes College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n\n\n{{England-poet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{unreferenced|date=June 2015}}\n'''Henry Forbes Summers''' (18 August 1911 in [[Harrogate]], [[Yorkshire]] \u2013 22 December 2005 in [[Basingstoke]], [[Hampshire]]), aka '''Hal Summers''', was a senior British civil servant. He published several volumes of [[poetry]].\n\nSummers was educated at [[Fettes College]], [[Edinburgh]] and [[Trinity College, Oxford]]. He joined the Ministry of Health in 1935.  He was Private Secretary to [[Aneurin Bevan]] while he was Minister of Health, during the passage of the National Health Bill, 1945.\n\nHe moved to the [[Ministry of Housing and Local Government]] on its creation and was promoted to Under-Secretary in 1955.  This ministry was later absorbed into the [[Secretary of State for the Environment|Department of the Environment]].  He was made a [[Order of the Bath|CB]] in 1961 and retired in 1971.\n\n== Publications ==\n*''Smoke After Flame'', 1944\n*''Hinterland'', 1947\n*''Poems in Pamphlet IV: Visions of Time'', 1952\n*''Tomorrow is my Love'', 1978\n*''The Burning Book'', 1982\n*''Brevities'', 1991\n\nHis most popular poems include \"My Old Cat\" (voted one of Britain's favourite 20th-century poems in a [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] poll), \"The Beginners\" and \"The Seed\".\n\n==References==\n* [[Who's Who (UK)|Who was Who]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Summers, Hal}}\n[[Category:Private secretaries in the British Civil Service]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Ministry of Health (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Ministry of Housing and Local Government]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Department of the Environment]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Fettes College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n\n\n{{England-poet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hal_Summers"}
{"title_page": "2018 Connecticut House of Representatives election", "text_new": "{{Infobox Election\n| election_name      = 2018 Texas House of Representatives election\n| country            = Connecticut\n| type               = legislative\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = \n| previous_year      = 2016\n| next_election      = \n| next_year          = 2020\n| seats_for_election = All 151 seats in the [[Connecticut House of Representatives]]\n| election_date      = {{Start date|2018|11|6}}\n| image1             = [[File:Joe Aresimowicz.jpg|150x196px]]\n| leader1            = [[Joe Aresimowicz]]\n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| leaders_seat1      = 30th district ([[Berlin, Connecticut|Berlin]])\n| last_election1     = 80\n| seats1             = 92\n| seat_change1       = {{gain}} 12\n| image2             = \n| leader2            = [[Themis Klarides]]\n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| leaders_seat2      = 114th district ([[Woodbridge, Connecticut|Woodbridge]], [[Orange, Connecticut|Orange]], and [[Derby, Connecticut|Derby]])\n| last_election2     = 71\n| seats2             = 59\n| seat_change2       = {{loss}} 12\n| map_image          = 2018 Connecticut State House of Representatives Election.svg\n| map_size           = 350px\n| map_caption        = \n| title              = Speaker\n| before_election    = [[Joe Aresimowicz]]\n| before_party       = Democratic Party (United States)\n| after_election     = [[Joe Aresimowicz]]\n| after_party        = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsCT}}\n\nThe '''2018 Connecticut House of Representatives election''' was held on Tuesday, November 6, 2018 to elect members to the [[Connecticut House of Representatives]], one from each of the state's 151 [[Connecticut General Assembly|General Assembly]] districts. The date of this the election corresponded with other elections in the state, including ones for [[2018 Connecticut gubernatorial election|governor]], [[2018 United States Senate election in Connecticut|U.S. Senate]], and the [[Connecticut Senate|Connecticut State Senate]]. Democrats retained control of the House of Representatives, winning 92 seats to the Republicans 59.<ref>https://authoring.ct.gov/-/media/SOTS/ElectionServices/StatementOfVote_PDFs/2018-SOV.pdf?la=en</ref>\n\nRepresentatives elected will serve a two-year term, beginning in January 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2018 United States elections}}\n\n[[Category:2018 Connecticut elections]]\n[[Category:Connecticut General Assembly elections]]\n[[Category:2018 state legislature elections in the United States|Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Election\n| election_name      = 2018 Texas House of Representatives election\n| country            = Connecticut\n| type               = legislative\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = \n| previous_year      = 2016\n| next_election      = \n| next_year          = 2020\n| seats_for_election = All 151 seats in the [[Connecticut House of Representatives]]\n| election_date      = {{Start date|2018|11|6}}\n| image1             = [[File:Joe Aresimowicz.jpg|150x196px]]\n| leader1            = [[Joe Aresimowicz]]\n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| leaders_seat1      = 30th district ([[Berlin, Connecticut|Berlin]])\n| last_election1     = 80\n| seats1             = 92\n| seat_change1       = {{gain}} 12\n| image2             = \n| leader2            = [[Themis Klarides]]\n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| leaders_seat2      = 114th district ([[Woodbridge, Connecticut|Woodbridge]], [[Orange, Connecticut|Orange]], and [[Derby, Connecticut|Derby]])\n| last_election2     = 71\n| seats2             = 59\n| seat_change2       = {{loss}} 12\n| map_image          = 2018 Connecticut State House of Representatives Election.svg\n| map_size           = 350px\n| map_caption        = \n| title              = Speaker\n| before_election    = [[Joe Aresimowicz]]\n| before_party       = Democratic Party (United States)\n| after_election     = [[Joe Aresimowicz]]\n| after_party        = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsCT}}\n\nThe '''2018 Connecticut House of Representatives election''' was held on Tuesday, November 6, 2018 to elect members to the [[Connecticut House of Representatives]], one from each of the state's 151 [[Connecticut General Assembly|General Assembly]] districts. The date of this the election corresponded with other elections in the state, including ones for [[2018 Connecticut gubernatorial election|governor]], [[2018 United States Senate election in Connecticut|U.S. Senate]], and the [[Connecticut Senate|Connecticut State Senate]]. Democrats retained control of the House of Representatives, winning 92 seats to the Republicans 59.<ref>https://authoring.ct.gov/-/media/SOTS/ElectionServices/StatementOfVote_PDFs/2018-SOV.pdf?la=en</ref>\n\nRepresentatives elected will serve a two-year term, beginning in January 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2018 United States elections}}\n\n[[Category:2018 Connecticut elections]]\n[[Category:Connecticut General Assembly elections]]\n[[Category:2018 state legislature elections in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "UruGhan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Fixing category for state legislature elections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_Connecticut_House_of_Representatives_election"}
{"title_page": "Merchant republic", "text_new": "{{copyedit|date=August 2013}}\n{{Distinguish|Maritime republic}}\n[[File:Repubblica di Venezia.png|thumb|Territories of the Republic of Venice in the 15th and 16th centuries]]\n[[File:Repubblica di Genova.png|thumb|Expansion of Genoa in the Mediterranean Sea]]\n[[File:Repubbliche marinare - fondachi anconitani.png|thumb|Trade routes and warehouses of the merchant republic of Ancona]]\n\nThe '''Merchant Republic''' is the collective name of a number of important [[city-states]] which flourished in [[Italy]] and [[Dalmatia]] in the [[Middle Ages]]. Traditionally, the major four were [[Amalfi]], [[Pisa]], [[Genoa]] and [[Venice]], whose coats of arms appear in the flag of the [[Marina Militare]] (Italian Navy). These city states competed with each other both militarily and commercially. From the 10th to the 13th centuries they built fleets of ships both for their own protection and to support extensive trade networks across the Mediterranean, and had an essential role in the Crusades. As they found themselves in competition, these republics engaged in shifting alliances and warfare. A modern scholar has referred to Venice as a \"city without territory\" and a \"merchant republic.\" It is said that \"the government was that of a joint-stock trading company, the Doge its president, the Senate its board of directors, the populace its shareholders\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Broadening the Horizons of Chinese History: Discourses, Syntheses, and Comparisons|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=RLloK7hHiGAC&pg=PA75|accessdate=27 August 2013|year=1999|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-0348-7|page=75}}</ref>\n\nThe four classic merchant republics in Italy listed above, are usually listed in that order, reflecting the temporal sequence of their dominance. However, other towns in Italy also have a history of being merchant republics, though historically less prominent. These include [[Gaeta]], [[Ancona]], [[Molfetta, Italy|Molfetta]], [[Trani]] and, in [[Dalmatia]], [[Republic of Ragusa|Ragusa]] and [[Zara]]. \"Lord Novgorod the Great\", as it was called by the Russians, was a rich Russian merchant-republic in the thirteenth century. It extended its dominion over vast territories in the northern parts of the country, but it continued to invite princes from the House of Rurik to be its military governors and thus remained linked with the rest of the nation.<ref name=\"Zernov1978\">{{cite book|author=Nicolas Zernov|title=The Russians and Their Church|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=JTqWtaoxAZMC&pg=PA21|accessdate=26 August 2013|year=1978|publisher=St Vladimir's Seminary Press|isbn=978-0-913836-36-1|page=21}}</ref>\n\nThe merchant republic were city-states. They were generally [[republic|republics]] in that they were formally independent, though like the rest of medieval [[Europe]] subject to the powers of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] and/or the [[Catholic Church]]. All these cities during the time of their independence had similar (though not identical) systems of government in which the merchant class had considerable power. The welfare of a merchant republic was not compatible with the caprice inseparable from monarchy, which would subordinate trade to politics, diplomacy, fiscalism, and war. The 'state' that was built on traditional political institutions and the inherited and developing economic structure was far too atomistic and too vulnerable to harbour plans such as those attributed to it by Colbert.<ref name=\"PostanRich1967\">{{cite book|author1=Michael Mo\u00efssey Postan|author2=Edwin Ernest Rich|author3=H. J. Habakkuk|author3=C. H. Wilson|title=The Cambridge Economic History of Europe|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=fvA8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA531|accessdate=25 August 2013|year=1967|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-04507-0|page=531}}</ref>\n\nThe merchant republics were heavily involved in the [[Crusades]], providing support but most especially taking advantage of the political and trading opportunities resulting from these wars. The [[Fourth Crusade]], notionally intended to \u2018liberate\u2019 Jerusalem, actually entailed the Venetian conquest of Zara and [[Constantinople]], which transformed the city from a merchant republic to a maritime empire. No other event in the Middle Ages had so profound an impact on Venice.<ref name=\"Madden2008\">{{cite book|author=Thomas F. Madden|title=Enrico Dandolo and the Rise of Venice|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=sk9lvXUMHpYC&pg=PA117|accessdate=26 August 2013|date=1 April 2008|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-0-8018-9184-7|page=117}}</ref>\n\nEach of the merchant republics over time had dominion over different territories, including many of the islands in the [[Mediterranean]], especially [[Sardinia]] and [[Corsica]], lands on the [[Adriatic]] coast, and in the [[Near East]] and [[North Africa]]. The idea of a nation is peculiar to a merchant republic accustomed from early times to negotiating with other states for the privileges of extraterritoriality and concessions of a commercial nature. Thus, Venice had begun to construct its network of \"colonies\" in the eastern Mediterranean in the wake of the Crusades.<ref name=\"StillmanZucker1993\">{{cite book|author1=Yedida Kalfon Stillman|author2=George K. Zucker|title=New Horizons in Sephardic Studies|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=yq7VUKWz5dwC&pg=PA25|accessdate=27 August 2013|year=1993|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-1-4384-2131-5|page=25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n{{Government type}}\n\n[[Category:Forms of government]]\n", "text_old": "{{copyedit|date=August 2013}}\n{{Distinguish|Maritime republic}}\n[[File:Repubblica di Venezia.png|thumb|Territories of the Republic of Venice in the 15th and 16th centuries]]\n[[File:Repubblica di Genova.png|thumb|Expansion of Genoa in the Mediterranean Sea]]\n[[File:Repubbliche marinare - fondachi anconitani.png|thumb|Trade routes and warehouses of the merchant republic of Ancona]]\n\nThe '''Merchant Republic''' is the collective name of a number of important [[city-states]] which flourished in [[Italy]] and [[Dalmatia]] in the [[Middle Ages]]. Traditionally, the major four were [[Amalfi]], [[Pisa]], [[Genoa]] and [[Venice]], whose coats of arms appear in the flag of the [[Marina Militare]] (Italian Navy). These city states competed with each other both militarily and commercially. From the 10th to the 13th centuries they built fleets of ships both for their own protection and to support extensive trade networks across the Mediterranean, and had an essential role in the Crusades. As they found themselves in competition, these republics engaged in shifting alliances and warfare. A modern scholar has referred to Venice as a \"city without territory\" and a \"merchant republic.\" It is said that \"the government was that of a joint-stock trading company, the Doge its president, the Senate its board of directors, the populace its shareholders\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Broadening the Horizons of Chinese History: Discourses, Syntheses, and Comparisons|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=RLloK7hHiGAC&pg=PA75|accessdate=27 August 2013|year=1999|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-0348-7|page=75}}</ref>\n\nThe four classic merchant republics in Italy listed above, are usually listed in that order, reflecting the temporal sequence of their dominance. However, other towns in Italy also have a history of being merchant republics, though historically less prominent. These include [[Gaeta]], [[Ancona]], [[Molfetta, Italy|Molfetta]], [[Trani]] and, in [[Dalmatia]], [[Republic of Ragusa|Ragusa]] and [[Zara]]. \"Lord Novgorod the Great\", as it was called by the Russians, was a rich Russian merchant-republic in the thirteenth century. It extended its dominion over vast territories in the northern parts of the country, but it continued to invite princes from the House of Rurik to be its military governors and thus remained linked with the rest of the nation.<ref name=\"Zernov1978\">{{cite book|author=Nicolas Zernov|title=The Russians and Their Church|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=JTqWtaoxAZMC&pg=PA21|accessdate=26 August 2013|year=1978|publisher=St Vladimir's Seminary Press|isbn=978-0-913836-36-1|page=21}}</ref>\n\nThe merchant republic were city-states. They were generally [[republic|republics]] in that they were formally independent, though like the rest of medieval [[Europe]] subject to the powers of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] and/or the [[Catholic Church]]. All these cities during the time of their independence had similar (though not identical) systems of government in which the merchant class had considerable power. The welfare of a merchant republic was not compatible with the caprice inseparable from monarchy, which would subordinate trade to politics, diplomacy, fiscalism, and war. The 'state' that was built on traditional political institutions and the inherited and developing economic structure was far too atomistic and too vulnerable to harbour plans such as those attributed to it by Colbert.<ref name=\"PostanRich1967\">{{cite book|author1=Michael Mo\u00efssey Postan|author2=Edwin Ernest Rich|author3=H. J. Habakkuk|coauthors=C. H. Wilson|title=The Cambridge Economic History of Europe|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=fvA8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA531|accessdate=25 August 2013|year=1967|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-04507-0|page=531}}</ref>\n\nThe merchant republics were heavily involved in the [[Crusades]], providing support but most especially taking advantage of the political and trading opportunities resulting from these wars. The [[Fourth Crusade]], notionally intended to \u2018liberate\u2019 Jerusalem, actually entailed the Venetian conquest of Zara and [[Constantinople]], which transformed the city from a merchant republic to a maritime empire. No other event in the Middle Ages had so profound an impact on Venice.<ref name=\"Madden2008\">{{cite book|author=Thomas F. Madden|title=Enrico Dandolo and the Rise of Venice|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=sk9lvXUMHpYC&pg=PA117|accessdate=26 August 2013|date=1 April 2008|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-0-8018-9184-7|page=117}}</ref>\n\nEach of the merchant republics over time had dominion over different territories, including many of the islands in the [[Mediterranean]], especially [[Sardinia]] and [[Corsica]], lands on the [[Adriatic]] coast, and in the [[Near East]] and [[North Africa]]. The idea of a nation is peculiar to a merchant republic accustomed from early times to negotiating with other states for the privileges of extraterritoriality and concessions of a commercial nature. Thus, Venice had begun to construct its network of \"colonies\" in the eastern Mediterranean in the wake of the Crusades.<ref name=\"StillmanZucker1993\">{{cite book|author1=Yedida Kalfon Stillman|author2=George K. Zucker|title=New Horizons in Sephardic Studies|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=yq7VUKWz5dwC&pg=PA25|accessdate=27 August 2013|year=1993|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-1-4384-2131-5|page=25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n{{Government type}}\n\n[[Category:Forms of government]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merchant_republic"}
{"title_page": "Pomponius Secundus", "text_new": "'''Publius Pomponius Secundus''' was a distinguished statesman and poet in the reigns of [[Tiberius]], [[Caligula]], and [[Claudius]]. He was [[Roman consul|suffect consul]] for the ''[[nundinium]]'' of January-June 44, succeeding the ordinary consul [[Gaius Sallustius Crispus Passienus]] and as the colleague of the other ordinary consul, [[Titus Statilius Taurus (consul 44)|Titus Statilius Taurus]].<ref>Gallivan, \"The Fasti for the Reign of Claudius\", pp. 408, 424.</ref> Publius was on intimate terms with the [[Pliny the Elder|elder Pliny]], who wrote a biography of him, now lost.\n\n==Name==\nHis full name was '''Publius Calvisius Sabinus Pomponius Secundus''', as indicated by two fragmentary inscriptions from [[Germania Superior]].<ref>{{CIL|13|5201}}, {{CIL|13|11515}}.</ref> For some time, Pomponius' praenomen was uncertain; ''Publius'' was not a regular name of the Pompilii, and Olli Salomies discusses the possibility that it might have been '''Gaius''', but notes that a Publius Calvisius Sabinus was attested as existing in [[Spoletium]], and concludes that it is \"possible to assume with some confidence\" that he had been adopted by a Publius Calvisius Sabinus.<ref>Salomies, ''Adoptive and polyonymous nomenclature'', p. 114</ref>  That his praenomen was ''Publius'', at least after his adoption, seems to be confirmed by an inscription from [[Veii]], dating from his consulship, another from [[Cyrene, Libya|Cyrenae]], when he was [[proconsul]], and one from [[Mogontiacum]], when he was ''[[Legatus Augusti pro praetore]]''.<ref>{{CIL|11|3806}}, {{AE|1963|142}}, {{AE|1996|1175}}.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nPomponius' mother was [[Vistilia]], who by other marriages was the mother of [[Publius Suillius Rufus]] and the general [[Gnaeus Domitius Corbulo]]. The name of his father is not known, but [[Ronald Syme]] has suggested he could be either [[Gaius Pomponius Graecinus]], consul ''suffectus'' in AD 16, or his brother, [[Lucius Pomponius Flaccus]], consul ''ordinarius'' in 17.<ref>Syme, \"Domitius Corbulo\", p. 31</ref> Pomponius' brother, [[Quintus Pomponius Secundus]], was involved in various intrigues during the reigns of Tiberius and Claudius.  Quintus tried to protect his brother from Tiberius' displeasure.<ref>Tacitus, ''Annales'', vi. 18, xiii. 43.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nPomponius was one of the friends of [[Sejanus]], who was consul in 31, and on the latter's fall in October of that year, Pomponius was placed under house arrest, where he remained until Caligula released him.<ref>Cassius Dio, ''Roman History'', lix. 6, 29.</ref><ref>Tacitus, ''Annales'', v.8, vi.18.</ref> During either the reign of Caligula or Claudius he was governor of the public province of [[Creta et Cyrenaica]].<ref>Eck, \"\u00dcber die pr\u00e4torischen Prokonsulate in der Kaiserzeit\".</ref> It was during the reign of Claudius that Pomponius acceded to the consulship. He was afterwards governor of [[Germania Superior]] from the year 50 to 54; during his office Pomponius conducted a successful campaign, described by Tacitus, against the German [[Chatti]], where, after forty years, survivors of the [[Battle of the Teutoburg Forest]] were freed from slavery. For this he received ''ornamenta triumphalia''.<ref>Tacitus, ''Annales'', xii.27, 28</ref>\n\n==Writings==\nIt was by his tragedies that Secundus obtained the most celebrity. They are spoken of in the highest terms by Tacitus, [[Quintilian]], and the younger [[Pliny the Younger|Pliny]], and were read even in a much later age, as one of them is quoted by the grammarian [[Charisius]]. These tragedies were first put on the stage in the time of Claudius. Quintilian asserts that he was far superior to any writer of tragedies he had known, and [[Tacitus]] expresses a high opinion of his literary abilities.<ref>Tacitus, ''Annales'', xi. 13; ''Dialogus de Oratoribus'', 13.</ref><ref>[[Quintilian]], ''Institutio Oratoria'', x. 1. \u00a7 98.</ref><ref>Pliny the Younger, ''Epistulae'', iii. 5, vii. 17.</ref><ref>[[Charisius]], ''apud'' Bothe, ''Po\u00ebtae Scenici Latinorum Fragmenta'', vol. ii. p. 279.</ref>\n\nSecundus devoted much attention to the niceties of grammar and style, on which he was recognized as an authority. His subject matter was Greek, with one known exception, a ''[[praetexta]]'' called ''Aeneas''. Tragedians in the [[Julio-Claudian dynasty|Julio-Claudian]] and [[Flavian dynasty|Flavian]] periods typically were men of relatively high social status, and their works often expressed their political views under an insufficient veil of fiction. Only a few lines of his work remain, some of which belong to ''Aeneas''.<ref>Conte, ''Latin Literature'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=NJGp_dkXnuUC&pg=PA417&dq=%22Sabinus+Pomponius+Secundus%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3#v=onepage&q=%22Sabinus%20Pomponius%20Secundus%22&f=false pp. 417, 418].</ref><ref>Rudich, ''Political Dissidence under Nero'', p. 304.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pomponia (gens)]]\n* [[Calvisia gens]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Gaius Plinius Secundus ([[Pliny the Elder]]), ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Historia Naturalis]]'' (Natural History).\n* Marcus Fabius Quintilianus ([[Quintilian]]), ''[[Institutio Oratoria]]'' (Institutes of Oratory).\n* Gaius Plinius Caecilius Secundus ([[Pliny the Younger]]), ''[[Epistulae (Pliny)|Epistulae]]'' (Letters).\n* [[Tacitus|Publius Cornelius Tacitus]], ''[[Annals (Tacitus)|Annales]]'', ''[[Dialogus de oratoribus|Dialogus de Oratoribus]]'' (Dialogue on Oratory).\n* Lucius Cassius Dio Cocceianus ([[Cassius Dio]]), ''Roman History''.\n* [[Charisius|Flavius Sosipater Charisius]], ''Ars Grammatica'' (The Art of Grammar).\n* Friedrich Heinrich Bothe, ''Po\u00ebtae Scenici Latinorum Fragmenta'' (Fragments of the Latin Theatrical Poets), Heinrich Vogler, Halberstadt (1822).\n* ''[[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]'', [[William Smith (lexicographer)|William Smith]], ed., Little, Brown and Company, Boston (1849).\n* [[Theodor Mommsen]] ''et alii'', ''[[Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum]]'' (The Body of Latin Inscriptions, abbreviated ''CIL''), Berlin-Brandenburgische Akademie der Wissenschaften (1853\u2013present).\n* Ren\u00e9 Cagnat ''et alii'', ''[[L'Ann\u00e9e \u00e9pigraphique]]'' (The Year in Epigraphy, abbreviated ''AE''), Presses Universitaires de France (1888\u2013present).\n* [[Johann Carl Otto Ribbeck|Otto Ribbeck]], ''Geschichte der r\u00f6mischen Dichtung'', vol. iii. (1892); ''Tragicorum Romanorum fragmenta'' (1897).\n*[[Martin Schanz]], ''Geschichte der r\u00f6mischen Literatur'', vol. ii, p. 2 (1900).\n*[[Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel]], ''History of Roman Literature'' (Eng. trans.), pp. 284, 287 (1900).\n* [[Ronald Syme]], \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/299411 Domitius Corbulo]\", in ''[[Journal of Roman Studies]]'', vol. 60 (1970).\n* [[Werner Eck]], \"\u00dcber die pr\u00e4torischen Prokonsulate in der Kaiserzeit.  Eine quellenkritische \u00dcberlegung\" (Concerning the Praetorian Proconsulate of the Imperial Period: a Source-Critical Consideration), in ''Zephyr'', vol. 23/24, pp. 246 ''ff.'' (1972/1973).\n* Paul A. Gallivan, \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/638693 The ''Fasti'' for the Reign of Claudius]\", in ''[[Classical Quarterly]]'', vol. 28, pp. 407\u2013426 (1978).\n* Olli Salomies, ''Adoptive and Polyonymous Nomenclature in the Roman Empire'', Societas Scientiarum Fenica, Helsinki (1992).\n* Vasily Rudich, ''Political Dissidence under Nero'', Routledge, (1993).\n* Gian Biagio Conte, ''Latin Literature: A History'', JHU Press (1999).\n\n{{DGRBM|author=WS|title=Pomponius Secundus|volume=3|page=764|url=https://archive.org/stream/dictionaryofgree03smituoft#page/764/mode/2up}}\n{{1911|wstitle=Secundus, Publius Pomponius|volume=24|pages=573\u2013574}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gaius Sallustius Crispus Passienus]]&nbsp;II,<br/>and [[Titus Statilius Taurus (consul 44)|Titus Statilius Taurus]]|as=Ordinary consuls}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of early imperial Roman consuls|Suffect consul]] of the [[Roman Empire]]|years = 44 |regent1=[[Titus Statilius Taurus (consul 44)|Titus Statilius Taurus]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=''ignoti'', then<br/>[[Marcus Vinicius (consul 30)|Marcus Vinicius]] II,<br/>and [[Titus Statilius Taurus Corvinus]]|as=Ordinary consuls}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pomponius Secundus, Publius}}\n[[Category:Ancient Roman generals]]\n[[Category:Roman governors of Crete and Cyrenaica]]\n[[Category:Suffect consuls of Imperial Rome]]\n[[Category:Roman governors of Germania Superior]]\n[[Category:Roman-era poets]]\n[[Category:Silver Age Latin writers]]\n[[Category:Pomponii|Secundus, Publius]]\n[[Category:Calvisii|Pomponius Secundus, Publius]]\n[[Category:1st-century Romans]]\n[[Category:1st-century writers]]\n[[Category:1st-century Roman poets]]\n", "text_old": "'''Publius Pomponius Secundus''' was a distinguished statesman and poet in the reigns of [[Tiberius]], [[Caligula]], and [[Claudius]]. He was [[Roman consul|suffect consul]] for the ''[[nundinium]]'' of January-June 44, succeeding the ordinary consul [[Gaius Sallustius Crispus Passienus]] and as the colleague of the other ordinary consul, [[Titus Statilius Taurus (consul 44)|Titus Statilius Taurus]].<ref>Gallivan, \"The Fasti for the Reign of Claudius\", pp. 408, 424.</ref> Publius was on intimate terms with the [[Pliny the Elder|elder Pliny]], who wrote a biography of him, now lost.\n\n==Name==\nHis full name was '''Publius Calvisius Sabinus Pomponius Secundus''', as indicated by two fragmentary inscriptions from [[Germania Superior]].<ref>{{CIL|13|5201}}, {{CIL|13|11515}}.</ref> For some time, Pomponius' praenomen was uncertain; ''Publius'' was not a regular name of the Pompilii, and Olli Salomies discusses the possibility that it might have been '''Gaius''', but notes that a Publius Calvisius Sabinus was attested as existing in [[Spoletium]], and concludes that it is \"possible to assume with some confidence\" that he had been adopted by a Publius Calvisius Sabinus.<ref>Salomies, ''Adoptive and polyonymous nomenclature'', p. 114</ref>  That his praenomen was ''Publius'', at least after his adoption, seems to be confirmed by an inscription from [[Veii]], dating from his consulship, another from [[Cyrene, Libya|Cyrenae]], when he was [[proconsul]], and one from [[Mogontiacum]], when he was ''[[Legatus Augusti pro praetore]]''.<ref>{{CIL|11|3806}}, {{AE|1963|142}}, {{AE|1996|1175b}}.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nPomponius' mother was [[Vistilia]], who by other marriages was the mother of [[Publius Suillius Rufus]] and the general [[Gnaeus Domitius Corbulo]]. The name of his father is not known, but [[Ronald Syme]] has suggested he could be either [[Gaius Pomponius Graecinus]], consul ''suffectus'' in AD 16, or his brother, [[Lucius Pomponius Flaccus]], consul ''ordinarius'' in 17.<ref>Syme, \"Domitius Corbulo\", p. 31</ref> Pomponius' brother, [[Quintus Pomponius Secundus]], was involved in various intrigues during the reigns of Tiberius and Claudius.  Quintus tried to protect his brother from Tiberius' displeasure.<ref>Tacitus, ''Annales'', vi. 18, xiii. 43.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nPomponius was one of the friends of [[Sejanus]], who was consul in 31, and on the latter's fall in October of that year, Pomponius was placed under house arrest, where he remained until Caligula released him.<ref>Cassius Dio, ''Roman History'', lix. 6, 29.</ref><ref>Tacitus, ''Annales'', v.8, vi.18.</ref> During either the reign of Caligula or Claudius he was governor of the public province of [[Creta et Cyrenaica]].<ref>Eck, \"\u00dcber die pr\u00e4torischen Prokonsulate in der Kaiserzeit\".</ref> It was during the reign of Claudius that Pomponius acceded to the consulship. He was afterwards governor of [[Germania Superior]] from the year 50 to 54; during his office Pomponius conducted a successful campaign, described by Tacitus, against the German [[Chatti]], where, after forty years, survivors of the [[Battle of the Teutoburg Forest]] were freed from slavery. For this he received ''ornamenta triumphalia''.<ref>Tacitus, ''Annales'', xii.27, 28</ref>\n\n==Writings==\nIt was by his tragedies that Secundus obtained the most celebrity. They are spoken of in the highest terms by Tacitus, [[Quintilian]], and the younger [[Pliny the Younger|Pliny]], and were read even in a much later age, as one of them is quoted by the grammarian [[Charisius]]. These tragedies were first put on the stage in the time of Claudius. Quintilian asserts that he was far superior to any writer of tragedies he had known, and [[Tacitus]] expresses a high opinion of his literary abilities.<ref>Tacitus, ''Annales'', xi. 13; ''Dialogus de Oratoribus'', 13.</ref><ref>[[Quintilian]], ''Institutio Oratoria'', x. 1. \u00a7 98.</ref><ref>Pliny the Younger, ''Epistulae'', iii. 5, vii. 17.</ref><ref>[[Charisius]], ''apud'' Bothe, ''Po\u00ebtae Scenici Latinorum Fragmenta'', vol. ii. p. 279.</ref>\n\nSecundus devoted much attention to the niceties of grammar and style, on which he was recognized as an authority. His subject matter was Greek, with one known exception, a ''[[praetexta]]'' called ''Aeneas''. Tragedians in the [[Julio-Claudian dynasty|Julio-Claudian]] and [[Flavian dynasty|Flavian]] periods typically were men of relatively high social status, and their works often expressed their political views under an insufficient veil of fiction. Only a few lines of his work remain, some of which belong to ''Aeneas''.<ref>Conte, ''Latin Literature'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=NJGp_dkXnuUC&pg=PA417&dq=%22Sabinus+Pomponius+Secundus%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3#v=onepage&q=%22Sabinus%20Pomponius%20Secundus%22&f=false pp. 417, 418].</ref><ref>Rudich, ''Political Dissidence under Nero'', p. 304.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pomponia (gens)]]\n* [[Calvisia gens]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Gaius Plinius Secundus ([[Pliny the Elder]]), ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Historia Naturalis]]'' (Natural History).\n* Marcus Fabius Quintilianus ([[Quintilian]]), ''[[Institutio Oratoria]]'' (Institutes of Oratory).\n* Gaius Plinius Caecilius Secundus ([[Pliny the Younger]]), ''[[Epistulae (Pliny)|Epistulae]]'' (Letters).\n* [[Tacitus|Publius Cornelius Tacitus]], ''[[Annals (Tacitus)|Annales]]'', ''[[Dialogus de oratoribus|Dialogus de Oratoribus]]'' (Dialogue on Oratory).\n* Lucius Cassius Dio Cocceianus ([[Cassius Dio]]), ''Roman History''.\n* [[Charisius|Flavius Sosipater Charisius]], ''Ars Grammatica'' (The Art of Grammar).\n* Friedrich Heinrich Bothe, ''Po\u00ebtae Scenici Latinorum Fragmenta'' (Fragments of the Latin Theatrical Poets), Heinrich Vogler, Halberstadt (1822).\n* ''[[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]'', [[William Smith (lexicographer)|William Smith]], ed., Little, Brown and Company, Boston (1849).\n* [[Theodor Mommsen]] ''et alii'', ''[[Corpus Inscriptionum Latinarum]]'' (The Body of Latin Inscriptions, abbreviated ''CIL''), Berlin-Brandenburgische Akademie der Wissenschaften (1853\u2013present).\n* Ren\u00e9 Cagnat ''et alii'', ''[[L'Ann\u00e9e \u00e9pigraphique]]'' (The Year in Epigraphy, abbreviated ''AE''), Presses Universitaires de France (1888\u2013present).\n* [[Johann Carl Otto Ribbeck|Otto Ribbeck]], ''Geschichte der r\u00f6mischen Dichtung'', vol. iii. (1892); ''Tragicorum Romanorum fragmenta'' (1897).\n*[[Martin Schanz]], ''Geschichte der r\u00f6mischen Literatur'', vol. ii, p. 2 (1900).\n*[[Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel]], ''History of Roman Literature'' (Eng. trans.), pp. 284, 287 (1900).\n* [[Ronald Syme]], \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/299411 Domitius Corbulo]\", in ''[[Journal of Roman Studies]]'', vol. 60 (1970).\n* [[Werner Eck]], \"\u00dcber die pr\u00e4torischen Prokonsulate in der Kaiserzeit.  Eine quellenkritische \u00dcberlegung\" (Concerning the Praetorian Proconsulate of the Imperial Period: a Source-Critical Consideration), in ''Zephyr'', vol. 23/24, pp. 246 ''ff.'' (1972/1973).\n* Paul A. Gallivan, \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/638693 The ''Fasti'' for the Reign of Claudius]\", in ''[[Classical Quarterly]]'', vol. 28, pp. 407\u2013426 (1978).\n* Olli Salomies, ''Adoptive and Polyonymous Nomenclature in the Roman Empire'', Societas Scientiarum Fenica, Helsinki (1992).\n* Vasily Rudich, ''Political Dissidence under Nero'', Routledge, (1993).\n* Gian Biagio Conte, ''Latin Literature: A History'', JHU Press (1999).\n\n{{DGRBM|author=WS|title=Pomponius Secundus|volume=3|page=764|url=https://archive.org/stream/dictionaryofgree03smituoft#page/764/mode/2up}}\n{{1911|wstitle=Secundus, Publius Pomponius|volume=24|pages=573\u2013574}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gaius Sallustius Crispus Passienus]]&nbsp;II,<br/>and [[Titus Statilius Taurus (consul 44)|Titus Statilius Taurus]]|as=Ordinary consuls}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of early imperial Roman consuls|Suffect consul]] of the [[Roman Empire]]|years = 44 |regent1=[[Titus Statilius Taurus (consul 44)|Titus Statilius Taurus]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=''ignoti'', then<br/>[[Marcus Vinicius (consul 30)|Marcus Vinicius]] II,<br/>and [[Titus Statilius Taurus Corvinus]]|as=Ordinary consuls}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pomponius Secundus, Publius}}\n[[Category:Ancient Roman generals]]\n[[Category:Roman governors of Crete and Cyrenaica]]\n[[Category:Suffect consuls of Imperial Rome]]\n[[Category:Roman governors of Germania Superior]]\n[[Category:Roman-era poets]]\n[[Category:Silver Age Latin writers]]\n[[Category:Pomponii|Secundus, Publius]]\n[[Category:Calvisii|Pomponius Secundus, Publius]]\n[[Category:1st-century Romans]]\n[[Category:1st-century writers]]\n[[Category:1st-century Roman poets]]\n", "name_user": "P Aculeius", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing 'b' from AE template; link works without it, but not with it.", "url_page