]]\n|21\n|0\n|13,763\n|153\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Talladega County, Alabama|Talladega]]\n|38\n|1\n|82,291\n|46\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Tallapoosa County, Alabama|Tallapoosa]]\n|100\n|5\n|41,616\n|240\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Tuscaloosa County, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]]\n|120\n|0\n|194,656\n|62\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Walker County, Alabama|Walker]]\n|83\n|0\n|67,023\n|124\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Washington County, Alabama|Washington]]\n|12\n|1\n|17,581\n|68\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Wilcox County, Alabama|Wilcox]]\n|30\n|0\n|11,670\n|257\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Winston County, Alabama|Winston]]\n|4\n|0\n|24,484\n|16\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |3,734\n|'''99'''\n|4,903,185\n|76\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Alabama]]\n[[Category:2020 in Alabama|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Health in Alabama]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "CAWylie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Alabama"}
{"title_page": "Collapsology", "text_new": "'''Collapsology''' is the study of the collapse of the industrial civilisation and of what might follow this collapse<ref name=\"Servigne2015\">{{Cite book|title=Comment tout peut s'effondrer : petit manuel de collapsologie \u00e0 l'usage des g\u00e9n\u00e9rations pr\u00e9sentes|last=Servigne|first=Pablo|last2=Stevens|first2=Rapha\u00ebl|date=2015|publisher=Ed. du Seuil|isbn=9782021223316|location=|page=253|language=fr|oclc=908244398}}.</ref>. The concept has been developped in France by Yves Cochet and Agn\u00e8s Sina\u00ef, cofounders of the [[:fr:Institut Momentum|Momentum Institute]]. They define collapse as \n\n{{Quote|the process at the end of which basic needs (water, food, housing, clothing, energy, etc.) are no longer provided (at a reasonable cost) to a majority of the population by services framed by law<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beaudonnet|first=Laure|date=2018-08-06|title=La fin est proche: Qu'est-ce que la collapsologie, la \u00ab science \u00bb qui pr\u00e9dit l\u2019effondrement du monde ?|url=https://www.20minutes.fr/arts-stars/culture/2314475-20180806-fin-proche-collapsologie-science-predit-effondrement-monde|journal=20 Minutes|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\nThe word 'collapsology' has been coined and brought to the attention of the general public by Pablo Servigne and Rapha\u00ebl Stevens in their essay: ''Comment tout peut s\u2019effondrer. Petit manuel de collapsologie \u00e0 l\u2019usage des g\u00e9n\u00e9rations pr\u00e9sentes'' (How everything can collapse: A manual for our times<ref>{{Cite book|last=Servigne|first=Pablo|last2=Stevens|first2=Rapha\u00ebl|title=How Everything Can Collapse|publisher=Polity|year=2020|isbn=9781509541393|location=Cambridge|pages=}}</ref>), published in 2015<ref name=\"NYR\">{{cite magazine|last=Stetler |first=Harrison |date=2020-01-21 |title=\u2018Collapsologie\u2019: Constructing an Idea of How Things Fall Apart |url=https://www.nybooks.com/daily/2020/01/21/collapsologie-constructing-an-idea-of-how-things-fall-apart/|magazine=[[The New York Review of Books]]|location=New York City|publisher=Rea S. Hederman|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>. The term then gradually spread in the anglo-saxon world, although the concept had existed for a long time already (at least since 1972, with the publication of [[The Limits to Growth]]<ref name=\"Meadows-1972\"></ref>). \n\nCollapsology is part of the idea that mankind impacts his environment sustainably and negatively, and propagates the concept of ecological urgency, linked in particular to [[global warming]] and the [[biodiversity loss]]. Collapsologists believe, however, that the collapse of industrial civilization could be the result of a combination of different crises: environmental crisis, but also energy, economic, geopolitical, democratic, and other crises.<ref name=\"Futura\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.futura-sciences.com/planete/definitions/climatologie-collapsologie-18034/|title=Collapsologie|last=|date=|website=Futura|language=fr|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>.\n\nCollapsology is a transdisciplinary exercise involving [[ecology]], [[economics]], [[anthropology]], [[sociology]], [[psychology]], [[biophysics]], [[biogeography]], [[agriculture]], [[demography]], [[politics]], [[geopolitics]], [[bioarchaeology]], [[history]], [[futurology]], [[health]], [[law]] and [[art]]<ref name=\"Servigne20182\">{{cite web|title=La collapsologie avance\u2026|url=http://www.collapsologie.fr/?page_id=111|author=Rapha\u00ebl Stevens|website=collapsologie.fr|language=fr|access-date=13 May 2018|date=}}</ref>.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word \"collapsology\" is a neologism invented \"with a certain self-mockery\" <ref name=\"Servigne2015\"></ref> by Pablo Servigne, an agricultural engineer, and Rapha\u00ebl Stevens, an expert in the resilience of socio-ecological systems. It appears in their book published in 2015.\n\nIt is a [[portmanteau]] derived from the [[Latin]] collapsus, \"to fall, to collapse\" and from the suffix \"-logy\", [[logos]], put for \"study \" , which is intended to name an approach of a scientific nature.<ref>{{cite news | language = french | last = Faure | first = Sonya | title = Collapsologie [nom] : du latin, ''collapsus'', \u00ab\u00a0tomb\u00e9 d\u2019un seul bloc\u00a0\u00bb| newspaper = Lib\u00e9ration.fr|date = 11 June 2015|url = http://www.liberation.fr/debats/2015/06/11/collapsologie-nom-du-latin-collapsus-tombe-d-un-seul-bloc_1327524|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Mythological and religious foundations==\n{{detail|eschatology|end time|global catastrophic risk|flood myth|apocalyptic literature}}\nUnlike traditional eschatological thinking, collapsology is based on data and concepts from contemporary scientific work. It is not in line with the idea of the \"end of the world\" but makes the hypothesis of the end of ''a world'', that of the \"thermo-industrial civilization\".\n\n==Scientific basis==\nAs early as 1972, [[The Limits to Growth]]<ref name=\"Meadows-1972\">{{cite book|last1=Meadows|first1=Donella H|last2=Meadows|first2=Dennis L|last3=Randers|first3=J\u00f8rgen|last4=Behrens III|first4=William W|title=The Limits to Growth; A Report for the Club of Rome's Project on the Predicament of Mankind|date=1972|ref=Potomac Associates|publisher=Universe Books|location=New York|isbn=0876631650|url=https://issuu.com/dartmouth_college_library/docs/the_limits_to_growth?e=1347206/1573259|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, a report produced by MIT researchers, warned of the risks of exponential demographic and economic growth on a planet with limited resources.\n\nAs a [[Systems analysis|systemic approach]], collapsology is based on prospective studies such as The Limits of Growth, but also on the state of global and regional trends in the environmental, social and economic fields (such as the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change|IPCC]], [[Intergovernmental Science-Policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services|IPBES]] or Global Environment Outlook (GE) reports periodically published by the Early Warning and Assessment Division of the [[United Nations Environment Programme|UNEP]], etc.) and numerous scientific works<ref name=\"Servigne2015\"></ref> as well as various studies, such as \"A safe operating space for humanity\"<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Johan|last1=Rockstr\u00f6m|first2=Will|last2=Steffen|first3=Kevin|last3=Noone|first4=\u00c5sa|last4=Persson|title=A safe operating space for humanity|journal=Nature|volume=461|number=7263|date=2009-09-23|doi=10.1038/461472a|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/461472a|access-date=2020-04-07|pages=472\u2013475}}</ref> ; \"Approaching a state shift in Earth's biosphere\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barnosky|first1=Anthony D.|last2=Hadly|first2=Elizabeth A.|last3=Bascompte|first3=Jordi|last4=Berlow|first4=Eric L.|title=Approaching a state shift in Earth\u2019s biosphere|journal=Nature|volume=486|issue=7401|date=2012-06-06|issn=1476-4687|doi=10.1038/nature11018|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/nature11018|access-date=2020-04-07|pages=52\u201358|hdl=10261/55208|hdl-access=free}}</ref> , published in Nature in 2009 and 2012, \"The trajectory of the Anthropocene: The Great Acceleration\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Steffen |first1=Will |last2=Broadgate |first2=Wendy |last3=Deutsch |first3=Lisa |last4=Gaffney |first4=Owen |last5=Ludwig |first5=Cornelia |title=The trajectory of the Anthropocene : The Great Acceleration |journal=The Anthropocene Review |volume=2 |issue=1 |date=2015-01-16|issn=|doi=10.1177/2053019614564785|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/2053019614564785|access-date=2020-04-07|pages=81\u201398|hdl=1885/66463 |hdl-access=free }}</ref>, published in 2015 in The Anthropocene Review, and \"Trajectories of the Earth System in the Anthropocene\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Steffen |first1=Will |last2=Rockstr\u00f6m |first2=Johan |last3=Richardson |first3=Katherine |last4=Lenton |first4=Timothy M. |title=Trajectories of the Earth System in the Anthropocene |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=115 |issue=33 |date=2018-08-14 |issn=0027-8424|doi=10.1073/pnas.1810141115 |url=http://www.pnas.org/lookup/doi/10.1073/pnas.1810141115 |access-date=2020-04-07 |pages=8252\u20138259 |doi-access=free }}</ref>, published in 2018 in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America).\n\n== History ==\n=== Precursors (278 B.C.-2005) ===\nEven if this neologism only appeared in 2015 and concerns the study of the collapse of industrial civilization, the study of the [[societal collapse|collapse of societies]] is older and is probably a concern of every [[civilization]]. Among the works on this theme (in a broad sense) we can cite those of [[Berossus]] (278 B.C.), [[Pliny the Younger]] (79 AD), [[Ibn Khaldun]] (1375), [[Montesquieu]] (1734), [[Thomas Malthus|Thomas Robert Malthus]] (1766 - 1834), [[Edward Gibbon]] (1776), [[Georges Cuvier]], (1821), [[\u00c9lis\u00e9e Reclus]] (1905), [[Oswald Spengler]] (1918), [[Arnold Toynbee]] (1939), [[G\u00fcnther Anders]] (1956), [[Samuel Noah Kramer]] (1956), [[Leopold Kohr]] (1957), [[Rachel Carson]] (1962), [[Paul R. Ehrlich|Paul Ehrlich (1969)]], [[Donella Meadows]], [[Dennis Meadows]] & [[J\u00f8rgen Randers]] (1972), [[Ren\u00e9 Dumont]] (1973), [[Hans Jonas]] (1979), [[Joseph Tainter]] (1988), [[Al Gore]] (1992), [[Hubert Reeves]] (2003), [[Richard Posner]] (2004), [[Jared Diamond]] (2005).\n\n==== Arnold J. Toynbee (1889-1975) ====\nIn his monumental (initially published in twelve volumes) and highly controversial work of contemporary historiography entitled \"[[A Study of History]]\" (1972), [[Arnold Joseph Toynbee|Arnold J. Toynbee]] (1889-1975) deals with the genesis of civilizations (chap. 2), their growth (chap. 3), their decline (chap. 4), and their disintegration (chap. 5). According to him, the mortality of civilizations is trivial evidence for the historian, as is the fact that they follow one another over a long period of time.\n\n==== Joseph Tainter (born 1949) ====\nIn his book [[The Collapse of Complex Societies]], the anthropologist and historian [[Joseph Tainter]] (1949-) studies the collapse of various civilizations, including that of the Roman Empire, in terms of [[network theory]], [[energy economics|energy economics]] and [[Complex system|complexity theory]]. For Tainter, an increasingly complex society eventually collapses because of the ever-increasing difficulty in solving its problems.\n\n==== Jared Diamond (born 1937) ====\nThe american [[geographer]], [[synthetic theory of evolution|evolutionary]] [[biologist]] and [[physiologist]] [[Jared Diamond]] (1937- )  already evoked the theme of civilizational collapse in his book called ''[[Collapse: How Societies Choose to Fail or Succeed]]'', published in 2005. By relying on historical cases, notably the [[Rapa Nui people|Rapa Nui]] civilization, the [[Vikings]] and the [[Maya civilization]], Diamond argues that humanity collectively faces, on a much larger scale, many of the same issues as these civilizations did, with possibly catastrophic near-future consequences to many of the world's populations. This book has had a resonance beyond the United States, despite some criticism<ref>{{cite book|last1=Diamond|first1=Jarde|date=2005|title=Collapse: How Societies Choose to Fail or Succeed|isbn=978-0-241-95868-1|url=http://cpor.org/ce/Diamond%282005%29Collapse-HowSocietiesChooseFailureSuccess.pdf|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>.\n\n=== Modern collapsologists ===\nSince the invention of the term collapsology, many french personalities gravitate in or around the collapsologists' sphere. Not all have the same vision of civilizational collapse, some even reject the term \"collapsologist\", but all agree that contemporary industrial civilization, and the biosphere as a whole, are on the verge of a global crisis of unprecedented proportions. According to them, the process is already under way, and it is now only possible to try to reduce its devastating effects in the near future. The leaders of the movement are [[Yves Cochet]] and [[:fr:Agn\u00e8s Sina\u00ef|Agn\u00e8s Sina\u00ef]] of the [[:fr:Institut Momentum|Momentum Institute]] (a [[think tank]] exploring the causes of environmental and societal risks of collapse of the thermo-industrial civilization and possible actions to adapt to it), and Pablo Servigne and Rapha\u00ebl Stevens who wrote the essay ''How everything can collapse: A manual for our times''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Servigne |first=Pablo |last2=Stevens |first2=Rapha\u00ebl |title=How Everything Can Collapse|publisher=Polity|year=2020|isbn=9781509541393|location=Cambridge|pages=}}</ref>). Arnaud Dorthe is developing a new simulator that is a continuation of the MIT ''World Dynamics'' simulators, entitled ''Apocalypse Dynamics\u2122''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/abak-consulting/acknowledge/apocalypse-dynamics|last1=Dorthe|first1=Arnaud|title=Abak Consulting - Apocalypse dynamics|website=Abak Consulting|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>. \n\nBeyond the french collapsologists (or assimilated) mentioned above, we can quote: [[Aur\u00e9lien Barrau]] (astrophysicist), Philippe Bihouix (engineer, low-tech developer), [[Dominique Bourg]] (philosopher), Val\u00e9rie Cabanes (lawyer, seeking recognition of the crime of [[ecocide]] by the international criminal court), [[Jean-Marc Jancovici]] (energy-climate specialist), [[Paul Jorion]] (anthropologist, sociologist)...\n\nEven if the term remains rather unknown in the Anglo-Saxon world, many publications deal with the same topic (for example the recent David Wallace-Wells' bestseller ''[[The Uninhabitable Earth]]'', probably a mass-market collapsology work without using the term<ref name=\"NYR\"></ref>). It is now gradually spreading on general<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/collapse/comments/bg27r3/french_collapsology_if_you_didnt_know_this_in/|title=French collapsology \u2013 \u201cIf you didn\u2019t know this, in recent years France has seen a big societal movement around the idea that we are approaching a collapse.\u201d|date=2019-04-22|website=reddit.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and scientific<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/post/Collapsology_Have_you_heard_about |title=Collapsology! Have you heard about? |date=2019-07-07 |website=researchgate.net|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> english speaking [[social networking service|social networks]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[:Category:Civilizations]]\n[[:Category:Concepts]]\n", "text_old": "'''Collapsology''' is the study of the collapse of the industrial civilisation and of what might follow this collapse<ref name=\"Servigne2015\">{{Cite book|title=Comment tout peut s'effondrer : petit manuel de collapsologie \u00e0 l'usage des g\u00e9n\u00e9rations pr\u00e9sentes|last=Servigne|first=Pablo|last2=Stevens|first2=Rapha\u00ebl|date=2015|publisher=Ed. du Seuil|isbn=9782021223316|location=|page=253|language=fr|oclc=908244398}}.</ref>. The concept has been developped in France by Yves Cochet and Agn\u00e8s Sina\u00ef, cofounders of the [[:fr:Institut Momentum|Momentum Institute]]. They define collapse as \n\n{{Quote|the process at the end of which basic needs (water, food, housing, clothing, energy, etc.) are no longer provided (at a reasonable cost) to a majority of the population by services framed by law<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beaudonnet|first=Laure|date=2018-08-06|title=La fin est proche: Qu'est-ce que la collapsologie, la \u00ab science \u00bb qui pr\u00e9dit l\u2019effondrement du monde ?|url=https://www.20minutes.fr/arts-stars/culture/2314475-20180806-fin-proche-collapsologie-science-predit-effondrement-monde|journal=20 Minutes|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\nThe word 'collapsology' has been coined and brought to the attention of the general public by Pablo Servigne and Rapha\u00ebl Stevens in their essay: ''Comment tout peut s\u2019effondrer. Petit manuel de collapsologie \u00e0 l\u2019usage des g\u00e9n\u00e9rations pr\u00e9sentes'' (How everything can collapse: A manual for our times<ref>{{Cite book|last=Servigne|first=Pablo|last2=Stevens|first2=Rapha\u00ebl|title=How Everything Can Collapse|publisher=Polity|year=2020|isbn=9781509541393|location=Cambridge|pages=}}</ref>), published in 2015<ref name=\"NYR\">{{cite magazine|last=Stetler |first=Harrison |date=2020-01-21 |title=\u2018Collapsologie\u2019: Constructing an Idea of How Things Fall Apart |url=https://www.nybooks.com/daily/2020/01/21/collapsologie-constructing-an-idea-of-how-things-fall-apart/|magazine=[[The New York Review of Books]]|location=New York City|publisher=Rea S. Hederman|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>. The term then gradually spread in the anglo-saxon world, although the concept had existed for a long time already (at least since 1972, with the publication of [[The Limits to Growth]]<ref name=\"Meadows-1972\"></ref>). \n\nCollapsology is part of the idea that mankind impacts his environment sustainably and negatively, and propagates the concept of ecological urgency, linked in particular to [[global warming]] and the [[biodiversity loss]]. Collapsologists believe, however, that the collapse of industrial civilization could be the result of a combination of different crises: environmental crisis, but also energy, economic, geopolitical, democratic, and other crises.<ref name=\"Futura\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.futura-sciences.com/planete/definitions/climatologie-collapsologie-18034/|title=Collapsologie|last=|date=|website=Futura|language=fr|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>.\n\nCollapsology is a transdisciplinary exercise involving [[ecology]], [[economics]], [[anthropology]], [[sociology]], [[psychology]], [[biophysics]], [[biogeography]], [[agriculture]], [[demography]], [[politics]], [[geopolitics]], [[bioarchaeology]], [[history]], [[futurology]], [[health]], [[law]] and [[art]]<ref name=\"Servigne20182\">{{cite web|title=La collapsologie avance\u2026|url=http://www.collapsologie.fr/?page_id=111|author=Rapha\u00ebl Stevens|website=collapsologie.fr|language=fr|access-date=13 May 2018|date=}}</ref>.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word \"collapsology\" is a neologism invented \"with a certain self-mockery\" <ref name=\"Servigne2015\"></ref> by Pablo Servigne, an agricultural engineer, and Rapha\u00ebl Stevens, an expert in the resilience of socio-ecological systems. It appears in their book published in 2015.\n\nIt is a [[portmanteau]] derived from the [[Latin]] collapsus, \"to fall, to collapse\" and from the suffix \"-logy\", [[logos]], put for \"study \" , which is intended to name an approach of a scientific nature.<ref>{{cite news | language = french | last = Faure | first = Sonya | title = Collapsologie [nom] : du latin, ''collapsus'', \u00ab\u00a0tomb\u00e9 d\u2019un seul bloc\u00a0\u00bb| newspaper = Lib\u00e9ration.fr|date = 11 June 2015|url = http://www.liberation.fr/debats/2015/06/11/collapsologie-nom-du-latin-collapsus-tombe-d-un-seul-bloc_1327524|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Mythological and religious foundations==\n{{detail|eschatology|end time|global catastrophic risk|flood myth|apocalyptic literature}}\nUnlike traditional eschatological thinking, collapsology is based on data and concepts from contemporary scientific work. It is not in line with the idea of the \"end of the world\" but makes the hypothesis of the end of ''a world'', that of the \"thermo-industrial civilization\".\n\n==Scientific basis==\nAs early as 1972, [[The Limits to Growth]]<ref name=\"Meadows-1972\">{{cite book|last1=Meadows|first1=Donella H|last2=Meadows|first2=Dennis L|last3=Randers|first3=J\u00f8rgen|last4=Behrens III|first4=William W|title=The Limits to Growth; A Report for the Club of Rome's Project on the Predicament of Mankind|date=1972|ref=Potomac Associates|publisher=Universe Books|location=New York|isbn=0876631650|url=https://issuu.com/dartmouth_college_library/docs/the_limits_to_growth?e=1347206/1573259|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>, a report produced by MIT researchers, warned of the risks of exponential demographic and economic growth on a planet with limited resources.\n\nAs a [[Systems analysis|systemic approach]], collapsology is based on prospective studies such as The Limits of Growth, but also on the state of global and regional trends in the environmental, social and economic fields (such as the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change|IPCC]], [[Intergovernmental Science-Policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services|IPBES]] or Global Environment Outlook (GE) reports periodically published by the Early Warning and Assessment Division of the [[United Nations Environment Programme|UNEP]], etc.) and numerous scientific works<ref name=\"Servigne2015\"></ref> as well as various studies, such as \"A safe operating space for humanity\"<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Johan|last1=Rockstr\u00f6m|first2=Will|last2=Steffen|first3=Kevin|last3=Noone|first4=\u00c5sa|last4=Persson|title=A safe operating space for humanity|journal=Nature|volume=461|number=7263|date=2009-09-23|doi=10.1038/461472a|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/461472a|access-date=2020-04-07|pages=472\u2013475}}</ref> ; \"Approaching a state shift in Earth's biosphere\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barnosky|first1=Anthony D.|last2=Hadly|first2=Elizabeth A.|last3=Bascompte|first3=Jordi|last4=Berlow|first4=Eric L.|title=Approaching a state shift in Earth\u2019s biosphere|journal=Nature|volume=486|issue=7401|date=2012-06-06|issn=1476-4687|doi=10.1038/nature11018|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/nature11018|access-date=2020-04-07|pages=52\u201358|hdl=10261/55208|hdl-access=free}}</ref> , published in Nature in 2009 and 2012, \"The trajectory of the Anthropocene: The Great Acceleration\"<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Steffen |first1=Will |last2=Broadgate |first2=Wendy |last3=Deutsch |first3=Lisa |last4=Gaffney |first4=Owen |last5=Ludwig |first5=Cornelia |title=The trajectory of the Anthropocene : The Great Acceleration |journal=The Anthropocene Review |volume=2 |issue=1 |date=2015-01-16|issn=|doi=10.1177/2053019614564785|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/2053019614564785|access-date=2020-04-07|pages=81\u201398|hdl=1885/66463 |hdl-access=free }}</ref>, published in 2015 in The Anthropocene Review, and \"Trajectories of the Earth System in the Anthropocene\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Steffen |first1=Will |last2=Rockstr\u00f6m |first2=Johan |last3=Richardson |first3=Katherine |last4=Lenton |first4=Timothy M. |title=Trajectories of the Earth System in the Anthropocene |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=115 |issue=33 |date=2018-08-14 |issn=0027-8424|doi=10.1073/pnas.1810141115 |url=http://www.pnas.org/lookup/doi/10.1073/pnas.1810141115 |access-date=2020-04-07 |pages=8252\u20138259 |doi-access=free }}</ref>, published in 2018 in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America).\n\n== History ==\n=== Precursors (278 B.C.-2005) ===\nEven if this neologism only appeared in 2015 and concerns the study of the collapse of industrial civilization, the study of the [[societal collapse|collapse of societies]] is older and is probably a concern of every [[civilization]]. Among the works on this theme (in a broad sense) we can cite those of [[Berossus]] (278 B.C.), [[Pliny the Younger]] (79 AD), [[Ibn Khaldun]] (1375), [[Montesquieu]] (1734), [[Thomas Malthus|Thomas Robert Malthus]] (1766 - 1834), [[Edward Gibbon]] (1776), [[Georges Cuvier]], (1821), [[\u00c9lis\u00e9e Reclus]] (1905), [[Oswald Spengler]] (1918), [[Arnold Toynbee]] (1939), [[G\u00fcnther Anders]] (1956), [[Samuel Noah Kramer]] (1956), [[Leopold Kohr]] (1957), [[Rachel Carson]] (1962), [[Paul R. Ehrlich|Paul Ehrlich (1969)]], [[Donella Meadows]], [[Dennis Meadows]] & [[J\u00f8rgen Randers]] (1972), [[Ren\u00e9 Dumont]] (1973), [[Hans Jonas]] (1979), [[Joseph Tainter]] (1988), [[Al Gore]] (1992), [[Hubert Reeves]] (2003), [[Richard Posner]] (2004), [[Jared Diamond]] (2005).\n\n==== Arnold J. Toynbee (1889-1975) ====\nIn his monumental (initially published in twelve volumes) and highly controversial work of contemporary historiography entitled \"[[A Study of History]]\" (1972), [[Arnold Joseph Toynbee|Arnold J. Toynbee]] (1889-1975) deals with the genesis of civilizations (chap. 2), their growth (chap. 3), their decline (chap. 4), and their disintegration (chap. 5). According to him, the mortality of civilizations is trivial evidence for the historian, as is the fact that they follow one another over a long period of time.\n\n==== Joseph Tainter (born 1949) ====\nIn his book [[The Collapse of Complex Societies]], the anthropologist and historian [[Joseph Tainter]] (1949-) studies the collapse of various civilizations, including that of the Roman Empire, in terms of [[network theory]], [[energy economics|energy economics]] and [[Complex system|complexity theory]]. For Tainter, an increasingly complex society eventually collapses because of the ever-increasing difficulty in solving its problems.\n\n==== Jared Diamond (born 1937) ====\nThe american [[geographer]], [[synthetic theory of evolution|evolutionary]] [[biologist]] and [[physiologist]] [[Jared Diamond]] (1937- )  already evoked the theme of civilizational collapse in his book called ''[[Collapse: How Societies Choose to Fail or Succeed]]'', published in 2005. By relying on historical cases, notably the [[Rapa Nui people|Rapa Nui]] civilization, the [[Vikings]] and the [[Maya civilization]], Diamond argues that humanity collectively faces, on a much larger scale, many of the same issues as these civilizations did, with possibly catastrophic near-future consequences to many of the world's populations. This book has had a resonance beyond the United States, despite some criticism<ref>{{cite book|last1=Diamond|first1=Jarde|date=2005|title=Collapse: How Societies Choose to Fail or Succeed|isbn=978-0-241-95868-1|url=http://cpor.org/ce/Diamond%282005%29Collapse-HowSocietiesChooseFailureSuccess.pdf|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>.\n\n=== Modern collapsologists ===\nSince the invention of the term collapsology, many french personalities gravitate in or around the collapsologists' sphere. Not all have the same vision of civilizational collapse, some even reject the term \"collapsologist\", but all agree that contemporary industrial civilization, and the biosphere as a whole, are on the verge of a global crisis of unprecedented proportions. According to them, the process is already under way, and it is now only possible to try to reduce its devastating effects in the near future. The leaders of the movement are [[Yves Cochet]] and [[:fr:Agnes Sina\u00ef|Agnes Sina\u00ef]] of the [[:fr:Institut Momentum|Momentum Institute]] (a [[think tank]] exploring the causes of environmental and societal risks of collapse of the thermo-industrial civilization and possible actions to adapt to it), and Pablo Servigne and Rapha\u00ebl Stevens who wrote the essay ''How everything can collapse: A manual for our times''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Servigne |first=Pablo |last2=Stevens |first2=Rapha\u00ebl |title=How Everything Can Collapse|publisher=Polity|year=2020|isbn=9781509541393|location=Cambridge|pages=}}</ref>). Arnaud Dorthe is developing a new simulator that is a continuation of the MIT ''World Dynamics'' simulators, entitled ''Apocalypse Dynamics\u2122''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/view/abak-consulting/acknowledge/apocalypse-dynamics|last1=Dorthe|first1=Arnaud|title=Abak Consulting - Apocalypse dynamics|website=Abak Consulting|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>. \n\nBeyond the french collapsologists (or assimilated) mentioned above, we can quote: [[Aur\u00e9lien Barrau]] (astrophysicist), Philippe Bihouix (engineer, low-tech developer), [[Dominique Bourg]] (philosopher), Val\u00e9rie Cabanes (lawyer, seeking recognition of the crime of [[ecocide]] by the international criminal court), [[Jean-Marc Jancovici]] (energy-climate specialist), [[Paul Jorion]] (anthropologist, sociologist)...\n\nEven if the term remains rather unknown in the Anglo-Saxon world, many publications deal with the same topic (for example the recent David Wallace-Wells' bestseller ''[[The Uninhabitable Earth]]'', probably a mass-market collapsology work without using the term<ref name=\"NYR\"></ref>). It is now gradually spreading on general<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/collapse/comments/bg27r3/french_collapsology_if_you_didnt_know_this_in/|title=French collapsology \u2013 \u201cIf you didn\u2019t know this, in recent years France has seen a big societal movement around the idea that we are approaching a collapse.\u201d|date=2019-04-22|website=reddit.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> and scientific<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/post/Collapsology_Have_you_heard_about |title=Collapsology! Have you heard about? |date=2019-07-07 |website=researchgate.net|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> english speaking [[social networking service|social networks]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[:Category:Civilizations]]\n[[:Category:Concepts]]\n", "name_user": "Tithee.lefebvre", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eModern collapsologists", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collapsology"}
{"title_page": "AirDee", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = AirDee\n| image            = AirDee Pictured in 2019.jpg\n| image_upright    = 0.9\n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = Man standing against a wall. <!-- say who it is. See [[Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Accessibility/Alternative text for images#Importance of context]] for criticism of a bad alt text for a picture of [[Elizabeth II]]. -->\n| caption          = Ramolula in 2019\n| background       = non_performing_personnel\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Edward Mohlomi Ramolula\n| alias            = El Mucho\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1991|05|14}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bloemfontein, Free State]], South Africa\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Hip-Hop/Rap]]|[[Trap music|Trap]]|[[Electronic Music]]|}}\n| occupation       = [[Record Producer]], [[Instrumentalist]]\n| instrument       = {{hlist|[[Fl Studio]]|[[Keyboard instrument|Keyboards]]|[[Drum Machine]]|[[Propellerhead Reason]]|}}\n| years_active     = 2014\u2013present\n| label            = Cashtime (former), AirDee Global Production\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|DJ Vigilante|YoungstaCPT|[[Chad Da Don]]|[[Locnville]]|[[Cashtime]]|[[Nadia Nakai]] |Psyfo|Zoocci Coke Dope|Kid X|Focalistic}}|\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| module3          = \n}}\n'''Edward Mohlomi Ramolula''' (born May 14, 1991), known professionally as '''AirDee''' is a South African record producer, audio engineer and entrepreneur. He is the founder of his proprietorship AirDee Global Production  under which he produces and distributes music for many of the artists he works with. Ramolula has produced charting songs for artists including [[Locnville]], [[L-Tido]], [[K.O (rapper)|K.O]], [[Cashtime]] and [[Chad (rapper)|Chad Da Don]] among others.\n\nDuring the early 2010s Ramolula worked extensively with Psyfo producing a number of records notably 'Sorry Makhe' by DJ Vigilante and 'Imma Tell Her' by DJ Capital with the latter featuring Psyfo on the chorus. Ramolula is credited with production on [[IFani|iFani's]] Club 808 chart topping single 'Milli'. Most recently, in a bid to showcase his versatility Ramolula has been working with a lot of artists from other genre's. This has spawned the radio excitable single 'Better With Silence'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.warnermusic.co.za/multi-platinum-electro-hop-duo-locnville-present-their-latest-single-better-with-silence/|title=Multi-Platinum electro-hop duo, Locnville present their latest single 'Better With Silence' {{!}} Warner Music South Africa|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> which has Ramolula as a lead artist alongside [[Locnville]] with additional vocals by YoungstaCPT.\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn in  the judicial capital of South Africa, Ramolula's musical journey started to take shape when he was 16. He would often participate in beat boxing and hip hop cypher battles with school mates. From thereon he cemented his identity with hip hop music's  versatility and its massive cultural influence of trends and the found his passion among  general consensus with the youth, music. His skill was honed during university days where he used breaks between classes to master his craft and technical ability. During this period of his life Ramolula decided that, despite studying Agriculture at the Central University of Technology he would yield the farms for the love of music, a SlikourOnLife article<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slikouronlife.co.za/blog/4878/a-sit-down-with-producer-extraordinaire-airedeeglobal-with-mshelen_n|title=A Sit Down With Producer Extraordinaire @AiredeeGlobal With @MsHelen_N|website=www.slikouronlife.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> on Ramolula states \"He doesn't miss the farm\", a sitdown interview in which the producer shares how he used to randomly send beats to Rappers until he got his break. How growing up in a musical home he knew he would end up in the record industry.\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 2014 - 2016: ''Cashtime & Breakthrough hits'' ===\nRapper IFani met Ramolula through BlackBerry Messenger. They would subsequently work on 'Milli'. This song brought mainstream success for Ramolula after getting considerable airplay.Ramolula would then go on to work with Psyfo on the DJ Capital single 'Imma Tell Her'.<ref name=\":4\" /> It was during this period that Ramolula produced  'Sorry Makhe' by DJ Vigilante.<ref name=\":5\" /> Ramolula also had a brief stint as an in house record producer for Cashtime Life.\n[[File:Ramolula_in_studio_with_Chad.jpg|thumb|Ramolula (second from left) pictured with Kay Faith, Chad Da Don.]]\nRamolula won Best Producer at the Free State Golden Bean Awards<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Local/Express-News/golden-bean-pays-homage-to-fs-music-acts-20151110|title=Golden Bean pays homage to FS music acts|date=2015-11-11|website=News24|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> at the 2016 Ceremony.\n\n=== 2017 - 2019: ''AirDee Global Production and Electronic Sound'' ===\nIn 2017 Ramolula was named in the list of \"9 Producers behind South African Hip Hop Hits by Live Mag\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://livemag.co.za/9-young-south-african-producers-behind-your-favourite-hip-hop-hits/|title=9 young South African producers behind your favourite hip-hop hits \u2013 Livemag|website=livemag.co.za|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> He established his own sole proprietorship Production Company 'Airdee Global'  \"I want to put on as many kids from the Free State on before I die or retire\". Ramolula currently produces and distributes under his own company. Ramolula worked extensively with Chad Da Don and YoungstaCPT on the songs \"F.U\"<ref name=\":0\" /> and \"F.U.2\".<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://skinnygenestv.com/behindtheproducer-airdee-global-on-his-consistent-sound-x-chad-da-don-business-relationship/|title=#BehindTheProducer {{!}} AirDee Global On His Consistent Sound x Chad Da Don Business Relationship \u2013 Skinnygenes.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> In 2018 he released 'Better With Silence' as the lead artist alongside Locnville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peoplemagazine.co.za/celebrity-news/locnville-airdee-youngstacpt-join-forces-new-banger-better-silence/|title=Locnville, AirDee and YoungstaCPT Join Forces For New Banger 'Better With Silence'|date=2018-04-03|website=People Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> He reiterated what the collaboration meant to him as he has \"Always been a fan of the homies\", the song also featured YoungstaCPT.Ramolula then worked on YoungstaCPTs' 3T Album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://skinnygenestv.com/behindthealbum-airbreaks-down-his-production-work-on-youngsta-3t-album/|title=BehindTheAlbum {{!}} AirDee Global Breaks Down His Production Work On Youngsta 3T Album \u2013 Skinnygenes.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> Ramolula  produced a piano heavy  'Rare Intro' on the Zoocci Coke Dope and Die Mondez collaborative EP 'Die Dope'.<ref name=\":2\" /> Ramolula would then produce Sheba on Manu Worldstar's 'Young African Story' EP.<ref name=\":6\" /> Ramolula's last production effort of the decade was 'Run' by Free State rap duo StinoLeThwenny.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n<br />\n[[File:Ramolula_with_Kid_X_and_Chad_Da_Don.png|thumb|Ramolula with Kid X and Chad Da Don in 2019]]\n\n== Musical Style ==\nRamolula has described his sound as an influence of 'Lesenke' which is south-sotho word for corrugated iron. It is Kwaito influenced rhythm that brings a timeless element to the current Hip Hop sound. He also has strong command over the piano as can be heard throughout his output. The word Lesenke is also used to refer to Cassette tapes or classical music.\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== 2014 ===\n{{Discography|Name=DJ Capital - Imma Tell Her (featuring. Psyfo and KidX|Other info=produced with Psyfo|Released=2014}}<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.yomzansi.com/2014/03/28/new-music-dj-capital-ft-kid-x-and-psyfo-imma-tell-her/|title=NEW MUSIC : DJ Capital ft Kid X and Psyfo - Imma Tell Her {{!}} YoMZansi|last=tumza7gp|date=2014-03-28|website=www.yomzansi.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>{{Discography|Name=[[iFani]] - Milli|Released=2014|From Album=I Believes In Me|from Album=I Believes In Me}}{{Discography|Name=Notshi - We Don't Care|Released=2014}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slikouronlife.co.za/blog/12039/notshi-we-dont-care|title=Music: Notshi - We Don't Care|website=www.slikouronlife.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n=== 2015 ===\n{{Discography|Name=DJ Vigilante - Sorry Makhe (featuring. Yanga, [[L-Tido]] and Kid X|Released=2015}}<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://rarolae.com/new-video-djvigilantesa-ft-team_ltido-kidxoficial-maggz_za-itsyangachief-sorry-makhe/|title=NEW VIDEO: @DJVigilanteSA Ft. @Team_Ltido , @KidXoficial , @Maggz_ZA & @ItsYangaChief \u2013 Sorry Makhe|date=2014-11-25|website=Rarolae.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>{{Discography|Name=Money Nyce - Wildin' Out|Released=2015}}{{Discography|Released 2015|Name=[[Nadia Nakai]] - Whatever (featuring. DotCom and Psyfo)}}{{Discography|Name=AirDee - Hakuna Mathata(featuring. The Fraternity , Junior De Rocka and K2)|Released=2015}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slikouronlife.co.za/blog/1347/stream-and-download-airdee-ft-the-fraternity-k2-and-dj-junior-de-rocka|title=Stream And Download @AirDeeGlobal ft @TheFraternityZA, K_Toozle and @JuniorDeRocka Akuna Mathata|website=www.slikouronlife.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 ===\n{{Discography|Name=Sphectacula and Naves - Mnandi (featuring. [[Kwesta]])|Album=Kings Of The Weekend|Other info=as co-producer|Released=2016|from Album=Kings Of The Weekend}}{{Discography|Name=Exe - Everything On Me (featuring. Chad Da Don and AB Crazy)|Released=2016}}{{Discography|